com.apriori.collections

Class AssociativeArrayList<E,K>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractList<E>
        • java.util.ArrayList<E>
          • com.apriori.collections.AssociativeArrayList<E,K>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element in the list
    K - the type used for associative keys
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    AssociativeList<E,K>, Serializable, Cloneable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, List<E>, RandomAccess

    public class AssociativeArrayList<E,K>
extends ArrayList<E>
implements AssociativeList<E,K>
    An ArrayList that is also an AssociativeList. This collection maintains bidirectional mappings to/from list indices and associative keys using a HashMap (key to index) and a TreeMap (index to key).

        public Map<K,Integer> addAll(Map<? extends K,? extends E> mappedElements)
        Description copied from interface: AssociativeList
        Adds a collection of mapped entries from a map. The elements are added in whatever iteration order is for the specified map. They are added to the end of the list. Any key that was already associated with an element in the list will instead be associated with its corresponding value in the specified map. The returned map, if not empty, contains any such overwritten keys along with their previously associated list index.

      • nextKeyedIndex

        public int nextKeyedIndex(int start)
        Description copied from interface: AssociativeList
        Returns the next index in the list, that is greater than or equal to the specified index, that has an associated key. The following code construct can be used to iterate through the indexes with associative keys: 
         for (int i = list.nextKeyedIndex(0); i >= 0; i = list.nextKeyedIndex(i + 1)) {
   // i is an index associated with a key
 }
        Specified by:
        nextKeyedIndex in interface AssociativeList<E,K>
        Parameters:
        start - the starting index for searching for an index with a key
        Returns:
        the next index with a key that is greater than or equal to the specified starting index or -1 if no more keys exist
